<ea> = \#(An)\# \#d(An)\# \#d(An,Rx)\# \#([b,An],Rx,d)\# \#([b,An,Rx],d)\#
       \#addr\#
\end

screen( "Atari Memory Map" )
Atari Memory Map
----------------------------------------------------------------------
$00000000  \#Exception Vectors\# - \#Privileged\#
$00000400  \#System Variables\#  - \#Privileged\#
$00000800  \#ST RAM\# (size varies)
$00A00000  \#VMEbus\# (Mega STE)
$00E00000  System ROM (TT)
$00F00000  \#IDE Port\# (Falcon) - \#Privileged\#
$00FA0000  Cartridge ROM
$00FC0000  System ROM (ST)
$00FF8000  \#I/O Ports\#         - \#Privileged\#

$01000000  \#TT RAM\# (size varies)
$7FE00000  System ROM (Hades)
$80000000  PCI bus (Hades)
$FE000000  \#VMEbus\# (TT)
$FF000000  \#ST Compatible Image\#
\end

screen( capsensitive("ST RAM") )
ST RAM
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Memory addresses below $DFFFFF (ST RAM) can be accessed by both the
CPU and the video system, with the video system having priority.
Access is controlled by the \link("Memory Controller")MMU\# chip.

Addresses below $800 are \#Privileged\#.

Addresses between $A00000 and $DFFFFF are used for the \#VMEbus\# on a
Mega STE.

See also \#Atari Memory Map\# and \#TT RAM\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("TT RAM") )
TT RAM (FASTRAM)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... starts at $1000000, beyond the address space available to the
68000 CPU.  This memory is directly accessed by the CPU, not through
the \link("Memory Controller")MMU\# chip.  Consequently it is faster to access than \#ST RAM\#.

Since the video chips cannot access TT RAM at all, programs which
handle video images in their BSS segment must be loaded into \#ST RAM\#.
Programs which handle video images in heap memory must \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Malloc\#() from
\#ST RAM\#.

Since the DMA chip used for floppy and ACSI port I/O uses 24 bit
addresses, it also cannot access TT RAM.  TOS I/O functions use a
buffer in \#ST RAM\# and copy to/from TT RAM.

The header of an executable program file contains flags on whether
to load a program or satisfy calls to \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Malloc\#() using TT RAM (see
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Linker Options\#).

In addition, the TT supports a new function, \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Mxalloc\#(), which allows
one to specify whether to use \#ST RAM\# or TT RAM.

See also \#Atari Memory Map\#.
\end

screen( "System Variables" )
System Variables ($400 - $7FF)               -- \#Privileged\# --
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... are mostly of interest when writing device drivers (which are
already in Supervisor Mode).   Many variables can be accessed through
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")BIOS\# or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")XBIOS\# functions.

\#System Variables by Address\#
\#System Variables by Name\#

\#Disk Drivers\#
\#Device Drivers\#
\#Screen Dump\#
\#Vblank\#
\#Cookie Jar\#

'vector' is an address for executable code.
'address' is an address for a data structure or jump vector table.
'magic' must contain a certain value (memory validity test).
'control' is used by the OS to control operation.
'data' is set but not used by the OS.
'reserved' either not implemented or should not be modified.
\end

screen( "I/O Ports" )
I/O Ports  ($FF8000 - $FFFFFF)            -- \#Privileged\# --
----------------------------------------------------------------------
$FF8000  \#Memory Controller\# & \#Falcon Processor Control\#
$FF8200  \#Video Controller\#
$FF8400  \#TT Palette\#
$FF8600  \#ACSI and FDC\#
$FF8700  \#SCSI DMA Control\#
$FF8780  \#SCSI Controller\#
$FF8800  \#GI Sound Chip\#
$FF8900  \#DMA Sound Control\#
$FF8960  \#Real Time Clock\#
$FF8A00  \#Blitter Chip\#
$FF8C00  \#SCC DMA Control\# (Serial 2)
$FF8C80  \link("Serial Communications Control")Serial Communications Controller\#
$FF8E00  \#System Control Unit\#
$FF9200  \#Configuration Switches\# and \#Enhanced Joystick Ports\#
$FF9800  Falcon VIDEL Palette Registers
$FFA000  TT main board peripheral expansion
$FFA200  \#DSP Host Interface\#
$FFFA00  \#ST MFP\#
$FFFA40  \#Mega FPU\#
$FFFA80  \#TT MFP\#
$FFFC00  \#IKBD and MIDI Interface\#
\end

